Hope, they maintain a personal relationship with Jesus and build new forms of kinship and belonging. By becoming what they call "new creations," these men and women testify to religious transformation rather than changes in sexual desire or behavior. Straight to Jesus exposes how the Christian Right attempts to repudiate gay identity and political rights by using the ex-gay movement as evidence that "change is possible." Instead, Erzen reveals, the realities of the lives she examines actually undermine this anti-gay strategy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch work with gayszCaliforniazSan RafaelvCase studies. 0aEx-gay movementzCaliforniazSan RafaelvCase studies. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aborn again christians.  achristian conversions.  achristian lives.  achristian ministries.  achristian right.  achristianity.  aconservative christianity.  aevangelical christians.  aex gay ministries.  aex gay movement.  agay identity.  agay men.  aheterosexuality.  ahomosexuality.  ahuman rights.  ajesus.  alesbians.  algbtq.  amen and women.  anew hope ministry.  anonfiction.  apolitical rights.  areligious transformation.  aromantic relationships.  asame sex desire.  asexual conversions.  asexual desire.  asexuality.  asocial history.  atransnationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024581540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093905940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939059423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939059/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY